title: For Sale:  SWISS/BERN 1906/24 LUGER -- Matching/Original
postcontent: very nice original condition Swiss Luger. Manufactured at the government owned Waffenfabrik Bern factory, this is a Model 1906/24 chambered for the 7,65mm Parabellum (.30 Luger). It has the earlier style features including grip safety, no stock lug, and up-for-safe safety. The tapered barrel measures 120mm (approx. 4-3/4"). The area over the chamber is properly blank, the middle toggle link is marked "WAFFENFARBIK BERN" beneath a small Swiss cross. The Swiss cross is also found on the left side of the barrel, right side of receiver & grip frame, left side of the breech block, back of side plate, etc. The left side of the pistol has the Berner Probe proof, and a small square containing a small cross over the letter "M" (the control proof of Col. Muhlemann). The serial numbered parts are all matching, including those on the excellent bordered grips AND one of the magazines! Both of the magazines are nickel plated with wood bases (the spare mag is numbered "22").Overall condition is excellent with about 95% of the original blue finish remaining. There is some slight thinning to the finish at the edge of the muzzle and on the grip safety as well as some normal sharp edge wear. Good original straw finish remains on the trigger, safety, bolt lock, mag release and ejector. The grips are excellent with only very light wear, no cracks or chips. From the website:

Authentic Look of Old West - Modern Function 

All of the western gear I make is based on originals from the 19th century. Making my own patterns has allowed me to duplicate the styles and designs of cowboy gear that were once popular on the western frontier. Many of my dyes I mix myself to more closely resemble the colors that were used âback then.â I also use the same construction techniques that the saddle makers used 120 years ago. All of this ensures that my product is as authentic as I can make it. 

I only use the same western hardware that was available during the 19th century that is still made the same way today. My buckles are made either of solid brass or are nickel plated brass. The rivets I use are either âtubeâ rivets or copper bur rivets. 
Cowboy Action Holsters 

Back in âthe day,â cowboy holsters were designed to keep the gun in the holster regardless of weather, bouncing around on horseback etc. To accomplish this, the old holsters were generally made of thinner leather which "clung" to the gun. However, Cowboy Action Shooters want the gun to come out of the holster as quickly as possible, which means that the holster has to be made of thicker leather to hold its shape after the gun is removed. Although thicker leather works better, the edge doesnât look the same. 
My solution is to make the holster out of thicker leather, which holds its shape well so you can remove and replace the gun quickly; but I thin the leather at the edges to give the holster the same look as the originals.

Easy to ConcealBeretta Nano

Whether you like to carry inside the waistband, on the belt or in an ankle holster, the Nano will meet and surpass your needs. Personal Protection Made Easy

Easy to Use and Maintain

The Nano gives you easy assembly and disassembly, plus adjustable sights (no gunsmithing required) that allow you to always get on target even when you change ammo brands or weight. Also, the magazine-release button on the Nano can be easily reversed for left-handed use. In short, ergonomics, size, modular structure and power make the Nano the best-in-class concealed-carry and self-defense.

title: For Sale:  Sino-Soviet Chicom SKS
postcontent:
Hey all,

Background:

What you are looking at is an early production Chinese SKS, deemed the Sino-Soviet. This is determined by a lack of an arsenal marking of the use of Cyrillic alphabet in the serial. This gun lacks any arsenal marking.

This is not a cheap Chinese Norinco import, this is a real military Arsenal SKS. The ATF gave the greenlight to a batch of these that were sitting in Albania after the cold war. After the Sino-Soviet split, Albania sided with China to continue on Stalinization policies. In return, China provided Cold War aid in the forms of weapons and industrial aid. These SKS's were part of those aid packages. Once these SKS are gone, there won't be anymore authentic Russian or Chinese coming into the country due to the importation ban. Get your little piece of history today!

The gun:

Nation: China
Type: Type-56 Sino-Soviet SKS
Caliber: 7.62x39
Barrel: 20 inch chrome lined threaded and not pinned like a Russian.
Receiver: All Milled
Matching: Yes, 95 percent. (Original Gas Tube is Corroded and the piston gets hung up on it, but it will be included with the gun. A replacement with the matching upper handguard is currently on the gun.)
Accessories: Yes, includes original cleaning kit, original cleaning rod, and original bayonet assembly and bayonet.
Finish: 95 percent of bluing intact. Stock is in great condition.

Extra Information:

1. This gun has been fired 3-4 times to insure that rounds cycle reliably. This was due t the original gas tube not cycling and a replacement being needed.

2. This gun was originally packed in heavy cosmoline and I spent over 5-6 hours of my time clearing it away. You get it clean and functional without the mess.

3. This gun has not been sighted in or shot at the range. It will need to be sighted in, there are guides online on how to do this.

4. This gun is C&R eligible. 

Price: 400$

This gun cost me 320 before taxes, another 20 shipped and 20 for a transfer fee. I cleaned it out of the cosmoline and found a rare, Sino-Soviet, matching rifle beneath it. The stock is in great condition, (Which is a gamble with buying these guns) and the bluing is almost entirely intact except for the replacement gastube. 

I'm looking to break even on the gun and hoping it goes to a good home. Extra expenses came up, so I need to sell it much to my dismay, but my loss can be your gain.

For 400 bucks you get everything mentioned above and seen in the pictures, except for the sling which belongs to my AK47. I will also throw in 2 SKS stripper clips to go with the gun for free.

I would prefer a FTF transfer, but the buyer can pay to ship and do the transfer fees to have it sent out of state or to have it transferred at an ffl, the buyer will pay the transfer fee to have it done. 

I'm open to question or other offers.

Thanks for looking!
